# Data Talk — Project Analysis

## Architecture Overview

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Browser<br>HTML/JS/CSS] -->|REST API| B[Flask Server<br>server.py]
    B --> C[Gemini Service<br>gemini_service.py]
    B --> D[Data Service<br>data_service.py]
    B --> E[Code Executor<br>code_executor.py]
    C -->|API| F[Google Gemini]
    E -->|Subprocess| G[Sandboxed Python]
```

A vanilla HTML/JS frontend talks to a Flask backend (Python). The backend orchestrates a multi-phase AI pipeline: extract → generate code → execute in sandbox → interpret results.

---

## Strengths

| Area | Details |
|---|---|
| **Smart pipeline** | The 3-phase approach (extraction → code gen → interpretation) is well-designed. It sends lean schema to save tokens, generates executable Python, and then has Gemini interpret computed results — much better than asking the LLM to analyze raw data directly. |
| **Security** | `code_executor.py` has solid sandboxing: AST validation, blocked builtins/imports, subprocess isolation, and a 10s timeout. Good defense-in-depth. |
| **Data profiling** | `data_service.py` auto-detects dataset types (survey, time series, transactional) and generates domain-specific analysis suggestions — improves LLM output quality significantly. |
| **Token efficiency** | Schema context is dynamically sized (`max_tokens` budget), correlations are computed locally, and only metadata is sent to the LLM instead of raw data. |
| **UX polish** | Progress phases during AI processing, follow-up suggestions, chart annotations, drag-and-drop dashboard — good attention to user experience. |
| **Retry logic** | Code execution has 2 retry attempts with error feedback to Gemini, plus a text-only fallback — graceful degradation. |

---

## Weaknesses

| Area | Details |
|---|---|
| **No authentication** | `login.html` is purely cosmetic — any email/password logs you in. No sessions, tokens, or user management. |
| **Single-user only** | `AppState` is a global singleton. Multiple users would share chat history, active file, and query cache. |
| **No persistent storage** | Everything is in-memory (chat history saved as flat JSON). Server restart loses cache. No database. |
| **Large monolithic files** | `script.js` (1,350+ lines) and `dashboard.html` (1,470+ lines with inline CSS) are hard to maintain. |
| **No tests** | Zero test coverage. The sandbox, data parsing, and API endpoints are all untested. |
| **No error boundaries** | Frontend `fetch` calls have basic try/catch but no retry, no offline detection, no request timeout. |
| **File management** | Uploaded files accumulate forever in `/uploads`. No cleanup, no size quotas, no per-user isolation. |
| **Hardcoded config** | `API_BASE = "http://localhost:5000"` is hardcoded in JS. Won't work in any deployment scenario. |

---

## Suggested Improvements

### High Priority (Functionality)

1. **Real authentication** — Add Flask-Login or JWT-based auth. The login page already exists, just needs a real backend.
2. **Multi-file support** — Allow users to switch between uploaded files without re-uploading. Add a file picker to the Data Connector.
3. **File cleanup** — Auto-delete files older than N days, or add a delete button per file.
4. **Request timeout on frontend** — Add `AbortController` with a 60s timeout to prevent hung requests.

### Medium Priority (Code Quality)

5. **Split `script.js`** — Break into modules: `chat.js`, `dashboard.js`, `upload.js`, `particles.js`.
6. **Extract inline CSS from `dashboard.html`** — Move the ~930 lines of `<style>` into `styles.css` or a dedicated `dashboard.css`.
7. **Make `API_BASE` configurable** — Read from a `<meta>` tag or `/api/config` endpoint so deployment works.
8. **Add tests** — At minimum: `data_service` (parsing, profiling), `code_executor` (sandbox security), and API endpoint tests.

### Low Priority (Nice to Have)

9. **Export chat** — Allow exporting the full chat conversation as PDF or Markdown.
10. **Dark mode** — The CSS variable system is already in place (`--text-color`, etc.), making this straightforward.
11. **Streaming responses** — Use SSE or WebSocket to stream AI responses token-by-token instead of waiting for the full response.
12. **Rate limiting** — Add Flask-Limiter to prevent API abuse.

---

## Verdict

Data Talk is a **well-architected prototype** with a clever AI pipeline and good UX. The main gaps are around production-readiness: auth, multi-tenancy, persistence, and testing. The codebase is clean and readable but would benefit from modularization as it grows.
